Anish Kapoor (part 1) 
In early 2010 I saw @anish.kapoor ’s work for the first time at @guggenheim in NY. In fact, I was this recently arrived art history graduate that run to see a Kandinsky retrospective and in the middle of the show appeared that weird black square that was actually a hole into a kind of giant capsule 😳. Well, that is what I remember from ”Memory”, at the Guggenheim. Clearly, I knew nothing about contemporary art, yet... And I saw Kapoor’s blackest black for the first time.
With the years, I got more and more interested in contemporary art. I followed up the news and learned more about Anish Kapoor. As a Jewish Art art historian, it specially called my attention the news about the anti-Semitic graffiti in Paris and later the Genesis Prize in Israel, and Kapoor’s activism and solidarity with refugees. Somehow, this artist related to this ”category” - sorry for that, I know artists hate categories and tags 🙈- of Jewish artists, whose Jewish peoplehoodness (not to say identity) is expressed through art and actions that call the attention of the viewer and want to make a better world (’Tikun Olam’).
Anyway... When I saw that there was an exhibition in Buenos Aires I had to go. And finally, a couple of days before the show ends (hurry up, you have one more day!!), I was able to visit this great exhibition at PROA as I shared in my stories. I will share my experience at Surge and more pics, in my next post.

Al mismo tiempo presente y ausente. NO OBJETO (PUERTA) – Non-Object (Door) es un espejo cúbico que refleja en todos sus lados una forma distorsionada del espectador. Si se rodea con lentitud tendremos la inquietante experiencia de estar frente a un espejo que no nos refleja en absoluto.

La superficie espejada hace que la escultura casi desaparezca, fusionándose con el entorno. “Es uno de objetos más físicos de la exhibición pero a la vez es un objeto virtual, porque es una caja de imágenes del espacio”, sostiene Marcello Dantas, curador de la muestra de #AnishKapoor en Proa.

“Tenía que crear una forma que pudiera estar presente y no presente”, afirma #AnishKapoor sobre CUANDO ESTOY GESTANDO (When I am Pregnant, 1992).
.
La forma blanca curvada, simple, tiene un poder óptico sorprendente. Viéndola desde la distancia, no existe. A medida que empezamos a rodearla emerge de la pared, como un vientre de mujer embarazada.
.
“Esta aparición es el descubrimiento de cosas que están al borde de la percepción”, afirma el curador Marcello Dantas. “Se trata de la latencia, un momento en el que la energía transformadora tiene la posibilidad de emerger”.
.
Solo en una conexión directa y sensorial con la pieza el espectador podrá develar su configuración y su misterio.
.

La Cloud Gate (en español, Puerta de nube) es una escultura pública del artista indo-británico Anish Kapoor, es la pieza central de la Plaza AT&T en el Millennium Park en Chicago, Illinois, Estados Unidos.

Fue construida entre 2004 y 2006. Compuesta por 168 placas de acero inoxidable soldadas entre sí, en su exterior está pulido por lo que no tiene aparentemente costuras visibles. Se trata de una escultura de 10×20×13 m, y pesa 98 toneladas.

Coloquialmente se le apoda The Bean (El Frijol). .

Graduating from Hereford College of Art, Ben Pusey trained as an artist blacksmith and explored the world of kinetic art. He loves exploring kinetic forged metal sculpture because of the endless varieties of shapes and forms it is possible to make and the rich potential of orchestrating movement. He uses these properties to inform the work’s interest in creating experiences of ‘calm’ and ‘relaxation’. The forged steel process adds to these conceptual qualities, detaching us from our ‘hyperculture’. We are delighted to be showcasing Ben’s work for the first time in “A Fine Balance” in the stables at Houghton Hall this year. Opportunities for the public to view the collection and the farm are strictly limited. 
Funds raised from the open day will help us to use the power of music to help and heal people in need around New Zealand. Get your ticket today from NZTix or visit our website!

Al mismo tiempo presente y ausente. NO OBJETO (PUERTA) – Non-Object (Door) es un espejo cúbico que refleja en todos sus lados una forma distorsionada del espectador. Si se rodea con lentitud tendremos la inquietante experiencia de estar frente a un espejo que no nos refleja en absoluto.

La superficie espejada hace que la escultura casi desaparezca, fusionándose con el entorno. “Es uno de objetos más físicos de la exhibición pero a la vez es un objeto virtual, porque es una caja de imágenes del espacio”, sostiene Marcello Dantas, curador de la muestra de #AnishKapoor en Proa.

March Meet the Maker ~ Day 8: Love to Make

I love facetting my pots. I get my trusty knife and cut away at the surface to build up this irregular angular pattern. It takes a while and is hard on the fingers but it's immensely satisfying. Throwing big bowls is a very pleasing thing to do as well, making the ball of clay you start with transform into a great big container.

This bowl, along with a lot of other facetted pots, is heading over to @houghton_hall to be part of the selling exhibition run by @norfolk_by_design This year, @anish.kapoor will be exhibiting so I'm very much looking forward to visiting it.

In the early 90s, as a young trainee stone carver, Dan David was hugely influenced by the period’s dynamism, which saw him travelling to raves in fields, warehouses and squats throughout the UK and Europe. And, as with many others then questioning the status quo, he was deeply affected by the political atmosphere, actively participating in the Anti Criminal Justice Bill march. We are bringing a series of Dan’s sculptures to Houghton Hall this year that mark this important piece of social history. This size 9, Nike trainer is carved in sandstone from the Forest of Dean. Come and see more of Dan David’s sculptures in our pop up @houghton_hall this summer.

A Fine Balance serves to alert us to  our own social context and how significant that is in our outlook toward ‘the great outdoors’. Artists and makers will use current attitudes as well as depictions of the recent past that reveal our encounters with the natural landscape. It is through finding a variety of visualisations that we arrive at a greater understanding of the different claims made upon our immediate environment. -

This week’s AAM throwback exhibition is 1999’s “Powder”—a group exhibition featuring such artists as Vija Celmins, Andy Goldsworthy, Roni Horn, Anish Kapoor, William Kentridge, Yves Klein, Wolfgang Laib, Ana Mendieta, Ed Ruscha, and others, all of whom explored the multivalent meanings of powdery substances used as the basis for artworks since the days of the Lascaux cave paintings. From snow to pigment, gunpowder to white aspirin, graphite to carbon and even flour, each exhibiting “Powder” artist used uniquely different compositional materials.

One of the more surprising works? Meg Webster’s perfectly constructed “snow cone” right across the street from the Rubey Park bus terminal.

WIDE mouth

The two elliptical steel tube ends are identical, one standing vertical & this end horizontal.
There are heavy steel cables that run the 85m length supporting the pvc fabric.

My mechanical mind absorbs the design of the structure, an engineering marvel, enjoyed as an intense work of art inserted into a stunning landscape .... however, this view reminds me of an old joke about a WIDE mouth frog..... If I could only remember how it goes.... my mind is so simple.....

Anish Kapoor at PROA (part 2)
Hi there!! Here is my experience at ”Surge”, Anish Kapoor’s exhibition at PROA.
.
📌What: A selection of seven works by Anish Kapoor. They represent different materials and interactions with space and spectator.
📌When: Until March 1st 2020. Open 11 AM to 7 PM
📌Where: Fundación PROA, La Boca, Buenos Aires. All info at @fundacion_proa . 
I had my expectations and I came in with a background, and still could feel again that same feeling like when I stood in front of “Memory” back in January 2010.
First, the deepness and softness of the stones covered with the unique blue pigment in “Dragon”. You really feel the White Cube. You are entering to contemporary art. A great intro to the show.
Then, you move on and merge into another domain with “Svayambhu”. This time is space, with a different texture and materiality. Also time and sound. Movement. Does it really move?

✨📍 Guggenheim Museum - Bilbabo | 2nd pic: “Puppy” by Jeff Koons |
✨ What I found most interesting about the beautiful city, is its history. Bilbao from the 19th century up until the 1970s, was the most important industrial seaport in the Basque Country and the economy was booming.
✨ However, industries didn't adapt quickly enough to changing technical standards. The outdated dockyards and factories had to close. Factory buildings and ironworks were abandoned. Many workers and their families left the city, while others stayed without jobs.
✨Everything changed when at the beginning of the 1990s, the American Guggenheim Foundation, in search of a location for a European museum, was in negotiations with several important cities. Bilbao's authorities showed the strongest interest in the project. They realized what a huge opportunity the renowned temple of art could turn out to be for the run-down city.
✨ After both parties agreed to construct the museum the city started to change. The entire area along the Nervión River went through a complete face-lift within four years. The rusty dockyards disappeared, and were replaced by green spaces and promenades.
✨ Bilbao started blooming and hired other star architects to rejuvenate the city: Norman Forster built an entire subway line. Alvaro Siza designed a university building and an airport terminal, while the pedestrian bridge "Zubizuri," located near the museum, was created by Santiago Calatrava.

#anishkapoor ‘s #skymirror at @nottingham_playhouse is #ace 👍🏻
.
“Sky Mirror is a public sculpture by artist Anish Kapoor. Commissioned by the Nottingham Playhouse, it is installed outside the theatre in Wellington Circus, Nottingham, England. Sky Mirror is a 6-metre-wide (20 ft)-wide concave dish of polished stainless steel weighing 10 tonnes (9.8 long tons) and angled up towards the sky. Its surface reflects the ever-changing environment.

It took six years from the initial idea for a major new piece of public art to the unveiling of Sky Mirror on 27 April 2001, and cost £900,000. At the time, it was the most expensive piece of civic art funded by the National Lottery. It was manufactured in Finland.

In autumn 2007 the Nottingham Playhouse Sky Mirror was voted Pride of Place in a poll to find Nottingham's favourite landmark... From 19 September to 27 October 2006, a larger version of Sky Mirror was installed at Rockefeller Center in New York City. It had a 35 foot (11 m) diameter, stood three stories tall, and weighed 23 long tons (23 t). The convex side faced Fifth Avenue, the concave side the Rockefeller Center courtyard.

Versions of Sky Mirror also exist in the Hermitage Museum in Saint Petersburg, Russia and De Pont Museum of Contemporary Art in Tilburg, the Netherlands.

From 28 September 2010, Sky Mirror and three other Kapoor sculptures were exhibited in Kensington Gardens, London... The location of Sky Mirror was previously occupied by a sculpture by Henry Moore – a work that was donated by the artist, but had been removed for conservation in 1996. Kapoor's sculptures are guarded round-the-clock at a cost estimated to be £120,000 paid for by the Royal Parks Agency..” https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sky_Mirror

Ishi’s Light installation by Anish Kapoor in Tate Modern. Kapoor loves to play with light and depth perception (something I personally don’t have 😉). Sometimes, he uses pigments that absorb all light, leaving you unable to see whether you’re looking at a hole or something in 3D. Other times, he uses mirrors that are so clear that they make you a bit dizzy. Here, he created a large fibreglass egg that is curved like a crescent, almost inviting you to come in — and leave your role as a viewer and become a part of the art work. The inside isn’t actually black, but rather a red that is so deep that it turns into a visual illusion. The lacquer is incredibly glossy, distorting and reflective - contrasting with the matte outside - and light is reflected quite strongly. The effect when you’re standing in front of it is engulfing. Did you know that this piece is named after his son Ishan? 🙂 Check out my other Anish Kapoor posts by using #anishkapoorgr.

Great cities of the world: Monday’s choice - Bilbao 🇪🇸 .
Home to one of the greatest buildings in the world, the Guggenheim Museum is one of the most extraordinary spectacles at any time of day. In summer the shimmer from the rays of the sun on the titanium and steel structure creates a sensation of movement, as if the building is floating on water. At night the warm lights of the building are reflected in the pool below. The essence of ‘wow factor’. In fact, the art is almost secondary to the building. .
The city itself has so much more to offer, not least the outstanding variety of tapas available for ridiculously good prices. €30 will get a feast for two, including drinks. El Globo was our absolute favourite. Elbow your way in past the locals and a feast lies beyond. Tapas-bar-hopping is a recommended activity. You’ll get a real feel for the city. .

Ceramicist Laura Huston is showing a mixture of work some employing the technique of sgraffito to embellish the surface. Sgraffito means scratching a pattern into the slip, that has been applied to the leather hard clay body, to reveal the clay colour beneath. Her continual experimentation achieves subtle individuality. Cloud Gate is a public sculpture by Indian-born British artist Sir Anish Kapoor, that is located at Millennium Park in Chicago. The sculpture is nicknamed The Bean because of its shape.
Made up of 168 stainless steel plates welded together, its highly polished exterior has no visible seams. It measures 33 by 66 by 42 feet (10 by 20 by 13 m), and weighs 100 tons.

Son los últimos días para disfrutar de la muestra de Anish Kapoor en @fundacion_proa y este feriado de carnaval es una excelente oportunidad para ir 💥

Con obras seleccionadas por el curador Marcello Dantas que van de 1992 hasta la actualidad, la muestra abarca distintas series de la producción del artista y una amplia diversidad de materiales utilizados, tales como la cera, la piedra, el pigmento y el acero. Propone un recorrido a través de algunas de sus obras emblemáticas –algunas de ellas de gran presencia dramática (como la monumental Svayambhu,2007), y otras más elusivas, que se esfuman frente al espectador (When I’m Pregnant, 1992) o distorsionan el espacio que lo rodea (Non-object (Door), 2008). Jugando con dualidades opuestas –interior/exterior, presencia/ausencia, masculino/femenino— y con la percepción de las formas, Anish Kapoor coloca al público en un terreno incómodo, incierto.  En sus palabras, “…para crear un arte nuevo, debes crear un nuevo espacio... [ser] muy activo, encontrarte en varios estados de transformación”. A nivel internacional fue reconocido con el Premio Duemila por su participación en la 44° Bienal de Venecia, fue ganador del Premio Turner y recibió la distinción de Caballero, uno de los más altos honores de Inglaterra. En Argentina, sus obras fueron exhibidas en en 2017 en el Parque de la Memoria.

A lo largo de la exhibición se desarrolla una serie de programas públicos, con el objetivo de generar un importante intercambio de ideas, charlas, y actividades paralelas que aborden la obra de Anish Kapoor desde distintas perspectivas. La exposición viene acompañada de múltiples actividades de educación y extensión gratuitas para niños, jóvenes y adultos.

Se puede visitar de Martes a Domingos 11 - 19 hs Av Pedro Mendoza 1929.

#anishkapoor #redsolid #finland #thesnowshow #englandartist #installation #architectural #ephemere #landart #artcontemporain Une exposition temporaire basé dans deux endroits en Finlande - Keli et Romvaniemi. Lance Fung, un marchand d’art new-yorkais qui a eu l’idée de cette exposition. Cette exposition d’art environnemental contemporain, première du genre, remplace les matériaux familiers et permanents de l’art et de l’architecture par l’élément inhabituel et éphémère qu’est l’eau sous ses formes gelées... La libre communication entre les participants donnera lieu à des constructions uniques d’envergure significative - des œuvres qui défient les idées reçues et étonnent par leur beauté spatiale et visuelle. Jamais auparavant l’art et l’architecture n’ont eu pas à se rencontrer dans un tel contexte. Les participants sont confrontés à un double défi: celui de la collaboration avec leurs partenaires, ainsi que le défi structurel d’un nouveau matériau. La construction de fait grâce à Sappo Makinen, un ingénieur spécialisé de la glace et 120 étudiants volontaires internationaux qui les ont réellement construites. Cette pièce de Anish Kapoor, une baleine rouge devait être une grande structure creusée de couleur framboise avec des trous percés dans sa peau de cinq pouces d’épaisseur à travers lesquels les lumières brilleraient la nuit. Malheureusement, quelques heures après le fin des travaux, elle a implosé, affaibli par la chaleur des lumières à l’intérieur.

Built alongside the Nervion River, which runs through the city of Bilbao to the Cantabrian Sea, it is one of several museums belonging to the Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation and features permanent and visiting exhibits of works by Spanish and international artists. It is one of the largest museums in Spain.
✨The sculpture in this pic “Tall Tree & The Eye” was made by the great Anish Kapoor!

Do you recognize either of these sculptures? They're both associated with really BIG cities. 🤔 They're also both by Anish Kapoor, a British-Indian artist. ⁣
•⁣
•⁣
The first sculpture is the infamous Bean located in Chicago’s Millennium Park. (I visited mid July about 2 years ago so a picture without all the tourist is almost impossible) it sits at 33ft high, while its laid down. ⁣
•⁣

Gareth Hacon is a photographer based in North Norfolk, who studied graphic design and moved into photography with an interest in open and closed spaces. His work is concerned with the passage of thought leading from the expanse of large open spaces, seemingly impossible to capture.  Using time and patience these take form through his photographs harmonising composition, light and land to create a final photograph conveying thought and evoking awe.

We are showing Gareth’s work alongside other art photographers, artists and makers from across East Anglia in “A Fine Balance” opening 29 March, 2020 in the stables @houghton_hall See our website for more details, opening times and ticket prices for entering Houghton - where Anish Kapoor will be exhibiting in the main house and grounds this year. -

Fun factoid: this sculpture, created by Anish Kapoor, is officially named "Cloud Gate" but has been coined "The Bean" by Chicagoans...a name that Kapoor reportedly can't stand. I think this is particularly funny considering the fact that Kapoor bought an exclusive license to the 'blackest black' material so that other artists would have to pay him money to use it. This pissed off the art world so much that a designer named Stuart Semple created the 'pinkest pink' color and requires customers to make this legal declaration: “you are not Anish Kapoor, you are in no way affiliated to Anish Kapoor, you are not purchasing this item on behalf of Anish Kapoor or an associate of Anish Kapoor. To the best of your knowledge, information and belief this paint will not make its way into that hands of Anish Kapoor.⁠
If you order some I hope you love it. And please if you get a chance tell @anishkapoor_art to #ShareTheBlack"⁠
⁠
Ahhh...how I love art. :)⁠

The Cloud Gate - Chicago, IL. 
Whilst Anish Kapoor divides opinion amongst the art community for his work with Vantablack, the Cloud Gate or “Bean” as it’s often referred to is undeniably visually stunning. 
Situated in Millennium Park and the centre piece of the AT+T Plaza, it’s constructed from 168 stainless steel plates with no visible seams, stands 33 feet high and weighs just shy of 100 tons. 
The short film is shot from 100 individual high res raw frames processed out and pieced into a 7 second time lapse.

Anish Kapoor has Venus at 0° Aries — the Ur degree, the alpha … the very beginning of the whole Zodiac. And well, is here is a great big Mons Venus in Aries' own colour. Kapoor loves red.
.
.
.
He has North Node in Capricorn — a sign which often seems to feature in sculptor’s charts. One suspects his relationship with India must be pretty complex (but a source of inspiration) with Uranus on the South Node. It’s interesting that he manages to be extremely intellectual and popular — perhaps that is thanks to the Jupiter-Moon conjunction in Gemini (although one has to be a bit careful with that since there’s no birth time) trining Neptune in Libra.
.
.
.
He has the voice of a Piscean artist — he talks about illusions, dreams and actually having nothing to say. Curious and intriguing..
.
.
.

Today I ran the north end of the my neighborhood and discovered Millenium Park is my new neighborhood park. There were a few thousand people surrounding cloud gate and I was shy, so an onlooker took my photo with the park sign instead. Just as a well since I cant stand Anish Kapoor. 
There's something unbelievably humbling and thought-provoking about living in a city that seems as though it was built for Giants...of being surrounded by structures so large that they seem to dwarf even the most magnificent titans of industry. There's something spiritual about being here. Living imbthis city has solidified my belief that human capability is meant for more than amassing wealth. That the disparity of financial Security cannot be chalked up to luck or determination...that the physical realm we call reality is finite. But the energy that makes up our thoughts and our minds and our hearts and our spirit is infinite... And will exist long after these buildings crumble into ash. #anishkapoor #cloudgate #chicago #runningmotivation #endorphins
